Author: Michael Clementi

LOLMatchAnalysis.ipynb:
    Tool used to access the API of Riot Games to analyze League of Legends match data (particularly Classic games) using scraping and data science techniques
    Aims to find trends and correlations between each factor of games, and provide visuals to investigate the importance of gold income and feature priority

Usage:
    Make sure you have all required imports in your Python virtual environment before running
    See *IMPORTANT NOTE down below

    All data is taken from Riot Games Developer Tool: https://developer.riotgames.com/apis
    Riot API Endpoints used:
        AccountV1
        SummonerV4
        LeagueV4
        MatchV5
    
    Running:
        Main code begins after final defined function save_to_db

        Initially: 
            Wipes the 'league_data.db' for a fresh start when testing
            Gets the top players on the solo queue ladder, then gets their matches
                -> Change the 'top=' field when calling get_ladder to return the top # number of players requested
                -> Change the 'matches=' field when calling get_top_matches to return the requested # of matches per top player
                -> Change 'intervals' to get snapshots of gamestates at the requested minute intervals (recommended to start at 5 in five minute increments)
                    -> It will then process match info and save all match/team/participant info of each match to the database 'league_data.db'

        * Note that due to Riot Games's API limit, it may take a while to fetch a high amount of players and process a high number of games
            -> The program will post live updates of player fetching and game processes to ensure it's running correctly

        It will then get a requested player puuid from a player, as well as player puuids from recent players in the last _ # of matches
            -> Change the 'matches=' field when calling get_average_players to get _ # players from the last rquest # of matches
            -> Change the 'matches=' field when calling get_average_matches to get the recent _ # matches for every player return by get_average_players 

                *IMPORTANT NOTE: get_average_players gives up to 9 players per match not including the seed puuid. Less if people are partied together for multiple games
                    Due to working around API limits, this can VASTLY increase the run time with a moderate to high number of requested average players
                    -> For reference, running:
                        get_ladder(top=100) and then get_top_matches(ladder_df, matches=10) for ~1000 matches, then processing the matches
                            -> takes about 50 minutes total (assumming every player has 10 recent matches all Classic Draft/Ranked games)
                            -> From my testing this comes out to be ~750 matches for 35 minutes 
                        get_average_players(puuid=personal_puuid, matches=12), and then get_average_matches(average_players, matches=10) to get a similar number as the top matches
                            -> takes about the same amount of time, similar output
                        * Use this as reference when determining the ideal number of matches you want to process
                            A good starting point is 100 matches per ladder, which takes about 5 minutes

        After getting top ranked matches and average ranked matches, the program will then find correlations between each major game feature and wins
            Vizualizations of top teams/players vs average teams/players will be contructed to view importance of:
                Team-wide objectives
                Player-wide game features
                Static gold differentials at certain timeframes
                Dynamic game momentum at certain timeframes
